{{infobox artefact |name = Easter Island Statue |image =[[File:Angled View of the Hoa Hakananai'a Statue.JPG|400px]] |image_caption = Hoa Hakananai'a in the Wellcome Gallery. |material = Flow lava |size = Height: {{convert|2.42|m|ft}} |writing = |created = c. 1000-1600 CE |place = '[[Orongo]] ceremonial centre, [[Rapa Nui]] ([[Easter Island]]) |location = [[British Museum]], London, Gallery 24 |id = |registration = {{British-Museum-db|1869,1005.1|id=512302}} }}
'''Hoa Hakananai'a''' is a ''[[moai]]'' ([[Easter Island]] statue) housed in the [[British Museum]] in London. It was removed from ‘[[Orongo]], [[Rapa Nui]] (Easter Island) in November 1868 by the crew of the British ship {{HMS|Topaze|1858|6}},{{sfn|Van Tilburg|2006|p=37}} and arrived in England in August 1869.{{sfn|Van Tilburg|2006|p=3}} Though relatively small, it is considered to be typical of the island’s statue form,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Routledge|first1=K|title=The Mystery of Easter Island|date=1919|publisher=Sifton, Praed & Co|location=London|page=166}}</ref>{{sfn|Van Tilburg|2004|pp=45–47}} but distinguished by [[carvings]] added to the back, associated with the island birdman cult.{{sfn|Van Tilburg|1992|pp=56–59}} It has been described as a "masterpiece"<ref>{{cite book|last1=Métraux|first1=A|title=The Ethnology of Easter Island|date=1940|publisher=Bernice P. Bishop Museum|location=Honolulu|page=298}}</ref> and "without a doubt, the finest example of Easter Island sculpture".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Métraux|first1=A|title=Easter Island: A Stone-Age Civilisation of the Pacific|date=1957|publisher=Andre Deutsch|location=London|page=162}}</ref>
== Etymology ==
The statue was identified as Hoa Hakananai'a by islanders at the time it was removed, the British crew first recording the name in the form Hoa-haka-nana-ia or Hoa-haka-nama-ia.{{sfn|Van Tilburg|1992|p=41}} It has been variously translated from the Rapa Nui language ([[Polynesian languages|Polynesian]]) to mean ''breaking wave'',<ref>{{cite book|last1=Routledge|first1=K|title=The Mystery of Easter Island|date=1919|publisher=Sifton, Praed & Co|location=London|page=257}}</ref> ''surfriding'',{{sfn|Van Tilburg|1992|p=41}} ''surfing fellow''{{sfn|Davletshin|2012|pp=62–63}}<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Davletshin|first1=A|title=Images, which are not seen, and stolen friends, who steal: A reply to Van Tilburg and Arévalo Pakarati|journal=Rapa Nui Journal|date=2012|volume=26|issue=1|page=68}}</ref> or ''master wave-breaker'';<ref>{{cite web|title=RapaNui Sprache - Übersetzung Buchstabe N|url=http://www.osterinsel.de/35-rapanui-sprache-n.htm|website=Osterinsel}}</ref> and ''lost or stolen friend'',<ref>{{cite web|title=Hoa Hakananai'a ('lost or stolen friend') / Moai (ancestor figure)|url=https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details.aspx?objectId=512302&partId=1|website=British Museum}}</ref> ''stolen friend'' or ''hidden friend''{{sfn|Van Tilburg|1992|pp=41–42}} or ''doing robberies/mockeries friend''.{{sfn|Davletshin|2012|pp=62–63}}
== Provenance ==
When recorded in 1868, Hoa Hakananai'a was standing erect, part buried inside a freestone ceremonial "house" in the ‘[[Orongo]] village at the south-western tip of the island. It faced towards an extinct volcanic crater known as [[Rano Kau]], with its back turned to the sea.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Routledge|first1=K|title=Survey of the village and carved rocks of Orongo, Easter Island, by the Mana Expedition|journal=Journal of the Royal Anthropological Institute|date=1920|volume=50|pages=425–45|doi=10.2307/2843492}}</ref>{{sfn|Van Tilburg|1992|p=47}} It may have been made for this location, or first erected elsewhere before being moved to where it was found.{{sfn|Van Tilburg|1992|p=47}}{{sfn|Pitts|Miles|Pagi|Earl|2014|pp=7–10}}
== Description ==
Most statues on [[Rapa Nui]] are of a reddish tuff,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Van Tilburg|first1=J|title=Easter Island: Archaeology, Ecology and Culture|date=1994|publisher=British Museum|location=London}}</ref>{{sfn|Van Tilburg|2004|p=45}} but Hoa Hakananai'a is made from a block of dark grey-brown flow [[lava]].{{sfn|Pitts|Miles|Pagi|Earl|2014|p=3}} Though commonly described as [[basalt]], quarried near to where the statue was found,{{sfn|Van Tilburg|2004|p=45}} there is no record of petrological analysis to confirm this.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Van Tilburg|first1=J|last2=Pakarati|first2=C|title=Hoa Hakananai’a in detail: comment on A. Davletshin’s unconvincing assertion of an "overlooked image" on the ventral side of the ‘Orongo statue now in the British Museum|journal=Rapa Nui Journal|date=2012|volume=26|page=64}}</ref>{{sfn|Pitts|Miles|Pagi|Earl|2014|p=6}} It stands {{convert|2.42|m|ft|abbr=off}} high, is {{convert|96|cm|ft|abbr=on}} across, and weighs 4.2 tonnes.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hoa Hakananai'a ('lost or stolen friend') / Moai (ancestor figure)|url=https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details.aspx?objectId=512302&partId=1}}</ref>
The base of the statue, now concealed in a modern plinth, may originally have been flat, and subsequently narrowed, or was rough and tapering from the start.{{sfn|Van Tilburg|1992|pp=48–50}}{{sfn|Van Tilburg|2006|p=17}}{{sfn|Pitts|Miles|Pagi|Earl|2014|pp=6–7}}
Typical of Easter Island ''[[moai]]'', Hoa Hakananai'a features a heavy brow, blocky face with prominent nose and jutting chin, nipples, thin, lightly angled arms down the sides and hands reaching towards the stomach, which is near the base. It has a raised Y-shape in the centre of the chin, eyes hollowed out in a way characteristic of statues erected elsewhere on the island on ceremonial [[Easter Island#Stone platforms|''ahu'' platforms]], and long, rectangular stylised ears. A line around the base of the neck is interpreted as representing the clavicles;{{sfn|Van Tilburg|1992|pp=48–50}}{{sfn|Van Tilburg|2006|p=17}}{{sfn|Pitts|Miles|Pagi|Earl|2014|pp=6–7}} there is a semi-circular hollow for the suprasternal notch.
<gallery mode="packed" heights="300px"> File:Hoa Hakananai'a.jpg|The front of Hoa Hakananai'a's Head File:Front hand damage.jpg|Damage on Hoa Hakananai'a's hands at the front </gallery>
In its original form, the back is thought to have been plain, apart from a ''maro'', a belt or girdle, which consists of three raised lines and a circle above, and an M on a vertical line below. Near the base are slight indications of buttocks.{{sfn|Pitts|Miles|Pagi|Earl|2014|pp=6–7}}
<gallery mode="packed" heights="300px"> File:Lower Back of Hoa Hakananai'a.jpg|Lower Back of Hoa Hakananai'a showing the ''maro'', belt or girdle, and buttocks </gallery>
The top of the head is smooth and flat,{{sfn|Pitts|Miles|Pagi|Earl|2014|p=6}} and could originally have supported a ''[[pukao]]'', a cylindrical stone "hat". A flat round stone found near the site of the statue may have been such a hat,{{sfn|Pitts|Miles|Pagi|Earl|2014|p=23}} or, if the base was flat, a bed plate on which the statue once stood.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Routledge|first1=K|title=Survey of the village and carved rocks of 'Orongo, Easter Island, by the Mana Expedition|journal=Journal of the Royal Anthropological Institute|date=1920|volume=50|page=436|doi=10.2307/2843492}}</ref>
== Date ==
No Easter Island statues have been scientifically dated, but statue making in general is said to have begun by at least 1000 CE,{{sfn|Van Tilburg|2004|p=39}} and occurred mostly between 1300 and 1500 CE.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Fischer|first1=S|title=The Island at the End of the World|date=2005|publisher=Reaktion Books|location=London|page=33}}</ref> Manufacture is said to have ended by 1600 CE, when islanders began to topple them.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hoa Hakananai'a Easter Island statue|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/ahistoryoftheworld/objects/qV6Cpj1ITza54IbC7uij6Q|website=BBC}}</ref>
Episode 70 of the 2010 [[BBC Radio 4]] series [[A History of the World in 100 Objects]] describes the statue as being from 1000-1200 CE.
The Y on the chin and the clavicles are rare on Easter Island statues, and said to be late innovations.{{sfn|Van Tilburg|2004|p=47}}
== Carvings ==
The back of the statue, between the ''maro'' and the top of the head, is covered with relief carvings added at an unknown time after the statue was made.{{sfn|Van Tilburg|1992|pp=56–59}}{{sfn|Van Tilburg|2006|p=38–40}}{{sfn|Pitts|Miles|Pagi|Earl|2014|pp=11–19}} They are similar in style to [[petroglyphs]] on the native rock around the ‘Orongo village, where they are more common than anywhere else on the island.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lee|first1=G|title=Rock Art of Easter Island: Symbols of Power, Prayers to the Gods|date=1992|publisher=Institute of Archaeology, University of California|location=Los Angeles}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Horley|first1=P|last2=Lee|first2=G|title=Painted and carved house embellishments at ‘Orongo village, Easter Island|journal=Rapa Nui Journal|date=2009|volume=23|issue=2|pages=106–24}}</ref>
Either side and above the ring on the ''maro'' are two facing birdmen (''[[tangata manu]]''), stylised human figures with beaked heads said to represent frigate birds. Above these, in the centre of the statue’s head, is a smaller bird said to be a [[sooty tern]] (''[[manutara]]''). Either side of this is a ceremonial dance paddle (''ao''), a symbol of male power and prestige. Along the edge of the left ear is a third paddle, because of its smaller size possibly a ''rapa'' rather than an ''ao'', and on the right ear a row of four vulva symbols (''komari''). Y-shaped lines drop down from the top of the head.{{sfn|Van Tilburg|2004|pp=50–51}}{{sfn|Van Tilburg|2006|p=38}}
When first seen by Europeans, the carvings were painted red against a white background. The paint was totally or mostly washed off when the statue was rafted out to HMS ''Topaze''.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Horley|first1=P|last2=Lee|first2=G|title=Rock art of the sacred precinct at Mata Ngarau, ‘Orongo|journal=Rapa Nui Journal|date=2008|volume=22|issue=2|pages=112–14}}</ref>{{sfn|Pitts|2014|pp=39–48}}
Precise reading of these designs varies. The birdmen are popularly interpreted as [[Makemake (mythology)|Makemake]], a fertility god and chief god of the birdman cult.{{sfn|Van Tilburg|2004|p=22}} This cult, said to have replaced the older statue cult, was recorded by early European visitors.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Routledge|first1=K|title=The bird cult of Easter Island|journal=Folk-Lore|date=1917|volume=28|pages=335–55}}</ref>
It involved an annual competition to retrieve the first egg laid by migrating sooty terns. The contest was held at ‘Orongo, and the winning man became Makemake’s representative for the following year.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Flenley|first1=J|last2=Bahn|first2=P|title=The Enigmas of Easter Island|date=2003|publisher=Oxford University Press|location=Oxford|pages=175–77}}</ref>{{sfn|Van Tilburg|2004|p=23–25}} The last ceremony is thought to have been held in 1866 or 1867.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Routledge|first1=K|title=The Mystery of Easter Island|date=1919|publisher=Sifton, Praed & Co|location=London|pages=265–66}}</ref>
== New studies ==
After the most intensive survey of the statue to date, a more detailed interpretation of the carvings has been proposed.{{sfn|Pitts|Miles|Pagi|Earl|2014|pp=1–31}} The new survey, which followed an as yet unpublished [[3D scanner|laser scan survey]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Van Tilburg|first1=J|title=Hoa Hakananai’a laser scan project|url=http://www.eisp.org/10}}</ref> comprised a combination of [[Photogrammetry]] and [[Reflectance Transformation Imaging]], used to create high-resolution digital images in “two and a half” and three dimensions.{{sfn|Miles|Pitts|Pagi|Earl|2014|pp=596–605}}<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Pitts|first1=M|last2=Miles|first2=J|last3=Pagi|first3=H|last4=Earl|first4=G|title=Taking flight: the story of Hoa Hakananai’a|journal=British Archaeology|date=2013|volume=130|pages=24–31}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Pitts|first1=M|title=Last night in the Wellcome Gallery|url=http://mikepitts.wordpress.com/2012/02/16/last-night-in-the-wellcome-gallery}}</ref>
This allowed several details to be clarified. The Y-shaped lines at the top of the head are the remnants of two large ''komari'', partly removed by the other carvings, which were added at a later date. The small bird has a closed beak, not open as had often been described, and the foot of the left birdman has five toes, not six. There is a small, shallow carving below the left ear, which could be a ''komari'' or the head of an ''ao''. The beak of the right birdman comes to a short, rounded end, not a long pointed tip; the latter reading of the digital models was supported by a new interpretation of a photo of the statue taken in 1868.{{sfn|Pitts|2014|pp=39–48}}
<gallery mode="packed" heights="450px"> File:Petroglyphs on the back of the Hoa Hakananai'a Statue.jpg|Petroglyphs on the back of Hoa Hakananai'a </gallery>
The short beak has been contested,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Van Tilburg|first1=J|title=Comment on M. Pitts’ Hoa Hakananai’a, an Easter Island statue now in the British Museum, photographed in 1868'|journal=Rapa Nui Journal|date=2014|volume=28|pages=49–52}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lee|first1=G|last2=Horley|first2=P|last3=Bahn|first3=P|title=Comments on historical images of the moai Hoa Hakananai’a|journal=Rapa Nui Journal|date=2014|volume=28|pages=53–59}}</ref> and in turn the original study has been defended.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Miles|first1=J|title=Update on the Hoa Hakananai’a statue|url=http://acrg.soton.ac.uk/blog/4091}}</ref> In other studies, it has been proposed that the existing carvings on the back all but conceal four earlier birdman figures,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Horley|first1=P|last2=Lee|first2=G|title=Rock art of the sacred precinct at Mata Ngarau, ‘Orongo|journal=Rapa Nui Journal|date=2008|volume=22|issue=2|pages=112–13}}</ref> and that an engraved birdman fills the area of the front between the nipples and the hands.{{sfn|Davletshin|2012|pp=57–63}} The latter was rejected,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Van Tilburg|first1=J|last2=Pakarati|first2=C|title=Hoa Hakananai’a in detail: comment on A. Davletshin’s unconvincing assertion of an "overlooked image" on the ventral side of the ‘Orongo statue now in the British Museum|journal=Rapa Nui Journal|date=2012|volume=26|pages=64–66}}</ref> and defended.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Davletshin|first1=A|title=Images, which are not seen, and stolen friends, who steal: A reply to Van Tilburg and Arévalo Pakarati|journal=Rapa Nui Journal|date=2012|volume=26|issue=1|pages=67–68}}</ref> None of this can be seen in the new digital models.{{sfn|Pitts|Miles|Pagi|Earl|2014|p=11}}
The archaeologists behind the new digital study also proposed a new way to read the main composition. It was suggested that the elements worked together to portray the birdman ceremony, with the left birdman figure male, the right female (two of the four “egg gods”), and the bird above them their new-hatched fledgling. “Meanwhile the entire statue has become Makemake, its face painted white… in the manner of the human birdman”.{{sfn|Pitts|Miles|Pagi|Earl|2014|pp=26–28}} One group of critics described this interpretation as “interesting, thought provoking and even somewhat poetic”, but, while “greatly impressed by the work”, rejected the proposals.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lee|first1=G|last2=Horley|first2=P|last3=Bahn|first3=P|title=Comments on historical images of the moai Hoa Hakananai’a|journal=Rapa Nui Journal|date=2014|volume=28|pages=53–59}}</ref>
<gallery mode="packed" heights="450px"> File:Close up of the bird beaks.jpg|Close up of the carvings identifying the male (left) and female (right) birdman, with their fledgling above, as proposed in a disputed interpretation. Also seen in this image are the two large earlier ''komari'' that extend onto the top of the statue's head </gallery>
== Online viewers==
The archaeologists behind the new digital study have released online viewers of the [http://sketchfab.com/models/9e7c7d1481b54cb6b029a286a4f7357f Photogrammetry model] captured and the Reflectance Transformation Imaging datasets. The latter represent the [http://www.southampton.ac.uk/~jm1706/Front/viewer.html front],[http://www.southampton.ac.uk/~jm1706/Back1/viewer.html lower back], [http://www.southampton.ac.uk/~jm1706/Back2/viewer.html middle back], [http://www.southampton.ac.uk/~jm1706/Back3/viewer.html upper back] and the [http://www.southampton.ac.uk/~jm1706/Back4/viewer.html back of the head]. These viewers allow for the dissemination of the results to stimulate discussion.
== Recent history ==
Hoa Hakananai'a was found in November 1868 by officers and crew from the British Royal Navy ship {{HMS|Topaze|1858|6}}.{{sfn|Van Tilburg|2006|pp=26–37}} When first seen, it was buried up to about half its height or even more.{{sfn|Pitts|Miles|Pagi|Earl|2014|p=23}}<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lee|first1=G|last2=Horley|first2=P|last3=Bahn|first3=P|title=Comments on historical images of the moai Hoa Hakananai’a|journal=Rapa Nui Journal|date=2014|volume=28|pages=54–55}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Horley|first1=P|last2=Lee|first2=G|title=Rock art of the sacred precinct at Mata Ngarau, ‘Orongo|journal=Rapa Nui Journal|date=2008|volume=22|issue=2|pages=113–14}}</ref> It was dug out, dragged down from Rano Kau on a sledge, and rafted out to the ship.{{sfn|Van Tilburg|2006|p=37}}
It was photographed while HMS ''Topaze'' was docked in Valparaiso, Chile, from back{{sfn|Pitts|2014|pp=39–48}} and front.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lee|first1=G|last2=Horley|first2=P|last3=Bahn|first3=P|title=Comments on historical images of the moai Hoa Hakananai’a|journal=Rapa Nui Journal|date=2014|volume=28|pages=56–57}}</ref> At that time Commodore Richard Ashmore Powell<ref>https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details.aspx?objectId=512302&partId=1</ref>, captain of the ''Topaze'', wrote to the British Admiralty offering the statue as a gift.{{sfn|Van Tilburg|2006|p=3}}
HMS ''Topaze'' arrived in [[Plymouth]], England, on 16 August 1869. The Admiralty offered the statue to [[Queen Victoria]], who proposed that it should be given to the British Museum.{{sfn|Van Tilburg|2006|p=3}} It was mounted in a plinth and exhibited outside the museum’s front entrance, beneath the portico. During the Second World War, it was taken inside, where it mostly remained until 1966. In that year it was moved to the museum’s then Department of Ethnography, which had separate premises in Burlington Gardens. It returned to the British Museum site in 2000, when it was exhibited on a new, higher plinth in the Great Court, before moving to its present location in the Wellcome Trust Gallery (Room 24: Living and Dying).<ref>{{cite book|last1=Wilson|first1=D|title=The British Museum: A History|date=2002|publisher=British Museum|location=London}}</ref>{{sfn|Van Tilburg|1992|p=4–5}} It has been suggested that the statue was originally erected at a slightly different angle, so that the top of the head would have been exactly horizontal.{{sfn|Pitts|Miles|Pagi|Earl|2014|pp=10–11}}
== In popular culture ==
* Hoa Hakananai'a has inspired artists, among them [[Henri Gaudier-Brzeska]]<ref>{{cite book|last1=Wilson|first1=D|title=The British Museum: A History|date=2002|publisher=British Museum|location=London|page=226}}</ref> and [[Henry Moore]], who was filmed talking about the statue in 1958.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wyver|first1=J|title=Lost encounter|date=2013|url=http://www.illuminationsmedia.co.uk/2013/09/lost-encounter/}}</ref> Moore commented on its “tremendous presence”, and that its makers “knew instinctively that a sculpture designed for the open air had to be big”.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Moore|first1=H|last2=Finn|first2=D|title=Henry Moore at the British Museum|date=1981|publisher=British Museum|location=London}}</ref>[[Ron Mueck]] exhibited his Mask II in front of Hoa Hakananai'a in 2008/09.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ron Mueck|url=https://www.britishmuseum.org/the_museum/museum_in_london/london_exhibition_archive/statuephilia/ron_mueck.aspx}}</ref>
* [[Robert Frost]] wrote a poem about it called "The Bad Island – Easter".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Fagan|first1=D|title=Critical Companion to Robert Frost|date=2007|publisher=Facts on File|location=New York|pages=37–38}}</ref>
* The English artist Ronald Lampitt used it as a model for an illustration of Easter Island for ''Look and Learn'' magazine.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ronald Lampitt Archive|url=http://www.illustrationartgallery.com/acatalog/info_LampittEasterIsLL.html}}</ref>
* A set of six postage stamps issued by the [[Royal Mail]] in 2003 to commemorate the 250th anniversary of the British Museum featured Hoa Hakananai'a alongside other Museum objects such as the [[Sutton Hoo helmet]] and a mask of [[Xiuhtecuhtli]].{{sfn|CollectGBStamps}}{{sfn|Daily Mail|2003}}
* It was selected by British Museum director Neil MacGregor as one of the 100 objects with which he told the history of the world.<ref>{{cite book|last1=MacGregor|first1=N|title=A History of the World in 100 Objects|date=2010|publisher=Allen Lane|location=London|pages=449–55}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Hoa Hakananai'a Easter Island statue|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/ahistoryoftheworld/objects/qV6Cpj1ITza54IbC7uij6Q}}</ref>
* In 2010 it was the target of a protest against [[BP]]’s handling of an oil spill in the Gulf of Mexico.<ref>{{cite web|last1=BBC|title='Oil slick' protest against BP at the British Museum|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10620821}}</ref>
== Controversy == The Rapa Nui people consider the statue to be stolen. In November of 2018 Tarita Alarcon Rapu, the Governor of Easter Island, asked the British Museum to return the statue. The Rapa Nui people have recently gained administration over their ancestral lands on Easter Island. The museum agreed to discuss the statue with representatives of the Rapa Nui people <ref>http://www.msn.com/en-us/news/world/easter-island-begs-british-museum-for-statue-return/ar-BBPUSHI?ocid=iehp</ref>. The museum does not list the statue as a gift in its digital archives, it is recorded as a collected artifact<ref>https://britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/collection_object_details.aspx?objectId=512302&partId=1</ref>.
